  reg({
    id: 'rn-perf-memory-leaks', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-performance',
    difficulty: 'senior', type: 'deep-dive',
    prompt: 'What are the recurring, RN-specific sources of memory leaks — listeners, timers, navigation retention — and how would you actually catch one in a real app?',
    answer: {
      core: `The recurring pattern across all three is the same: something registers a reference to a component/closure that outlives the component itself, so garbage collection can never reclaim it. The three most common concrete sources are event listeners/subscriptions never removed, timers (<code>setInterval</code>/<code>setTimeout</code>) never cleared, and navigation stacks retaining unmounted (but not garbage-collected) screen instances.`,
      mechanism: `<ul>
<li><strong>Listeners</strong>: <code>Dimensions.addEventListener</code>, a Firebase/analytics SDK's event subscription, a WebSocket's <code>onmessage</code> handler, an <code>EventEmitter.addListener</code> — each holds a reference to the callback closure (and therefore everything it closed over, often including the whole component instance) until explicitly removed. A screen visited 50 times over a session without removing its listener accumulates 50 live closures, each pinning its own render's worth of state in memory.</li>
<li><strong>Timers</strong>: a <code>setInterval</code> started in a component and never cleared keeps firing (and keeps its closure alive) after the component unmounts — often manifesting as a confusing "why is this state update happening on an unmounted screen" warning/crash well after the user navigated away, not just as pure memory growth.</li>
<li><strong>Navigation retention</strong>: React Navigation by default keeps prior stack screens mounted (not just their state, but their component tree) so back-navigation is instant — this is a deliberate, correct tradeoff, but a screen with a genuinely large retained subtree (a big image cache, a heavy list's rendered rows) sitting many levels deep in the stack is real, cumulative memory pressure across a long session, distinct from a "true" leak but with the same symptom.</li>
</ul>
Catching these in practice: watch heap growth across repeated navigate-in/navigate-out cycles to the same screen using Xcode Instruments' Allocations tool or Android Studio's Memory Profiler — a leak shows as a heap baseline that never returns to its pre-visit level after several forced GC passes, while normal retained-but-legitimate memory (navigation stack) plateaus at a bounded, explainable size.`,
      tradeoffs: `Aggressively unmounting/clearing everything on every navigation event (e.g., forcing all screens to fully unmount instead of using navigation's default retention) trades away instant back-navigation for lower peak memory — a real tradeoff on lower-memory devices with deep stacks, not a pure win, and should be a deliberate choice (e.g. <code>unmountOnBlur</code> on specific heavy screens) rather than a blanket policy.`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'A useEffect subscribes to something and the component seems to leak — what\'s the fix pattern, generically?', a: 'The effect\'s return function must synchronously undo whatever the effect did — removeListener for a listener, clearInterval/clearTimeout for a timer, unsubscribe/close for a subscription/socket — so that on unmount (or before the effect re-runs due to a dependency change) the prior registration is torn down before a new one (if any) is created.' },
        { q: 'How do you distinguish "navigation is retaining a screen on purpose" from "this is an actual leak"?', a: 'Check whether the retained memory is bounded and explainable — a fixed number of prior stack screens, roughly consistent in size — versus growing unboundedly with repeated visits to the SAME screen. A true leak shows heap growth proportional to visit count even after popping back to the same point in the stack repeatedly; legitimate stack retention plateaus.' }
      ],
      redFlags: `Treating "memory keeps growing" as automatically a leak without checking whether it\'s explainable navigation-stack retention; not knowing that a missing useEffect cleanup is the single most common source of this whole class of bug; assuming a leak is invisible/undetectable rather than reproducible via repeated navigate-in/navigate-out cycles under a memory profiler.`
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-perf-interaction-manager', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-performance',
    difficulty: 'core', type: 'deep-dive',
    prompt: 'What problem does InteractionManager actually solve, and how does it relate to newer options like startTransition for deferring non-urgent work?',
    answer: {
      core: `<code>InteractionManager.runAfterInteractions(callback)</code> defers a JS-thread task until any currently-running "interaction" (a registered animation or gesture) has finished, so that heavy setup work — say, fetching and processing data right after a screen-transition animation starts — doesn't compete with that animation for the single JS thread while it's mid-flight and visually most sensitive to jank. <strong>As of RN 0.84 (Feb 2026), <code>InteractionManager</code> itself is marked deprecated</strong> in the docs, with removal planned in a future release; the recommended replacement for "defer this JS-thread work until the runtime judges itself free" is the DOM-standard <code>requestIdleCallback</code> API, which RN now implements natively.`,
      mechanism: `<pre><code class="language-js">useEffect(() => {
  const task = InteractionManager.runAfterInteractions(() => {
    loadHeavyDataForThisScreen(); // waits until the nav transition animation is done
  });
  return () => task.cancel();
}, []);
</code></pre>
Anything driving a screen-transition/gesture animation (React Navigation's transition, or explicit calls via <code>InteractionManager.createInteractionHandle()</code>) registers itself as an in-flight "interaction"; <code>runAfterInteractions</code> callbacks simply wait in a queue until that count drops to zero, then run on the next tick. It's specifically about <em>sequencing relative to animations</em>, not a general low-priority scheduler — the callback still eventually runs as ordinary, un-prioritized JS-thread work once interactions clear, and if you never resolve/cancel the interaction handle (or an animation library doesn't register with InteractionManager at all), queued callbacks can be delayed indefinitely. <code>requestIdleCallback(callback)</code> is the newer, standards-based equivalent the 0.84 deprecation points teams toward for the "run this when the JS thread has spare idle time" case — but it answers a related, not identical, question: idle-time opportunistic scheduling, versus InteractionManager's explicit "wait for this specific interaction to finish" sequencing.`,
      tradeoffs: `<code>InteractionManager</code> predates React's own concurrent-rendering primitives and only understands "animation in flight or not" — it has no concept of priority levels or interruption the way React 18's <code>startTransition</code>/<code>useDeferredValue</code> do. For deferring a low-priority <em>render</em> (e.g., a big list re-render that shouldn't block a text input from feeling responsive), <code>startTransition</code> is the more precise, React-native (pun intended) tool since it lets the higher-priority update actually interrupt the lower-priority one mid-render — something InteractionManager's simple queue-until-done model can't do. That three-way distinction survives the 0.84 deprecation: new code should default to <code>requestIdleCallback</code> over the now-deprecated <code>InteractionManager</code> for idle-time deferral, but <code>requestIdleCallback</code> and <code>startTransition</code> still aren't interchangeable either — one defers arbitrary JS-thread work until idle, the other deprioritizes a React render relative to another React render.`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'Is InteractionManager obsolete now that React has startTransition?', a: 'Not entirely — they solve adjacent but different problems. InteractionManager sequences relative to imperative animations/gestures (things outside React\'s own render scheduling, like a native-driven transition); startTransition deprioritizes a React render relative to another React render. A screen transition animation plus a heavy data fetch afterward is still a reasonable InteractionManager use case, though as of RN 0.84 InteractionManager itself is deprecated in favor of requestIdleCallback for the general "defer until idle" role — that deprecation doesn\'t change the separate InteractionManager-vs-startTransition distinction, it just changes which API you\'d reach for on the sequencing side.' },
        { q: 'What happens if the callback passed to runAfterInteractions is itself expensive?', a: 'It still runs synchronously on the JS thread once interactions clear — InteractionManager only controls WHEN it runs relative to animations, not how it runs. A genuinely expensive callback can still cause its own jank once it fires; it may need to be chunked or moved off-thread separately.' },
        { q: 'Why was InteractionManager deprecated, and is requestIdleCallback a straight swap for it?', a: 'RN 0.84 deprecated it (removal planned) in favor of the DOM-standard requestIdleCallback, which the runtime now implements natively instead of leaving teams to hand-roll idle-time deferral. It\'s not a perfect drop-in for every existing use, though: requestIdleCallback triggers on general idle time, while runAfterInteractions specifically waited for a registered animation/gesture interaction to end — code relying on that exact "after this transition finishes" semantics may need to track the interaction itself rather than assume requestIdleCallback reproduces it.' }
      ],
      redFlags: `Describing InteractionManager as a general low-priority task scheduler with true preemption (it isn\'t — it\'s a simple "wait until interactions finish" queue); assuming it obsoletes startTransition or vice versa rather than recognizing they target different kinds of "later"; treating InteractionManager as current, non-deprecated guidance post-RN-0.84 instead of steering new code toward requestIdleCallback.`
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-perf-renderitem-keyextractor-bug', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-performance',
    difficulty: 'senior', type: 'spot-the-bug',
    prompt: 'This FlatList feels janky while scrolling and rows occasionally show stale content after the data updates. What\'s the perf bug?',
    code: "function ContactList({ contacts, onSelect }) {\n  return (\n    <FlatList\n      data={contacts}\n      // BUG 1: renderItem is a brand-new inline function every render of ContactList,\n      // so FlatList can never bail out of re-rendering every row via PureComponent/memo\n      // comparison — it always sees a \"new\" renderItem reference.\n      renderItem={({ item }) => (\n        <ContactRow\n          contact={item}\n          // BUG 1b: same problem one level down — a fresh arrow fn per row per render\n          onPress={() => onSelect(item.id)}\n        />\n      )}\n      // BUG 2: no keyExtractor, and `contacts` items don't have a top-level `key` —\n      // FlatList falls back to array index as the identity, so recycled native\n      // views get mismatched to the wrong logical item whenever the array is\n      // reordered/filtered/prepended, showing stale/wrong row content.\n    />\n  );\n}\n\nconst ContactRow = React.memo(function ContactRow({ contact, onPress }) {\n  return (\n    <Pressable onPress={onPress}>\n      <Text>{contact.name}</Text>\n    </Pressable>\n  );\n});",
    answer: "function ContactList({ contacts, onSelect }) {\n  const renderItem = useCallback(({ item }) => (\n    <ContactRow contact={item} onSelect={onSelect} />\n  ), [onSelect]);\n\n  const keyExtractor = useCallback((item) => item.id, []);\n\n  return (\n    <FlatList\n      data={contacts}\n      renderItem={renderItem}\n      keyExtractor={keyExtractor}\n    />\n  );\n}\n\nconst ContactRow = React.memo(function ContactRow({ contact, onSelect }) {\n  const handlePress = useCallback(() => onSelect(contact.id), [onSelect, contact.id]);\n  return (\n    <Pressable onPress={handlePress}>\n      <Text>{contact.name}</Text>\n    </Pressable>\n  );\n});",
    explanation: "Two independent bugs stacked on the same list. First, <code>renderItem</code> (and the <code>onPress</code> closure created inside it) is redefined as a brand-new function reference on every render of the parent — FlatList/its row-level memoization has no way to know that functionally-identical-looking new function is \"the same\" as last time, so every row re-renders on every parent re-render regardless of whether ContactRow is wrapped in React.memo. Hoisting renderItem out via useCallback (and pushing the per-row onPress construction down into ContactRow itself, built from stable props) restores referential stability so memo\'s shallow prop comparison can actually succeed. Second, and more seriously, there's no keyExtractor and the data items apparently have no key FlatList can infer, so it silently falls back to using the array index as each row's identity. Virtualized lists recycle the underlying native view for off-screen rows into new positions as you scroll — with a stable per-item key (item.id), the list knows exactly which logical item a recycled view now represents; with index-based identity, inserting, removing, reordering, or filtering the contacts array reassigns indices to different logical items, so a recycled row can flash the previous occupant's content until it catches up — the 'stale content after data updates' symptom. That's a correctness bug riding on top of the perf bug, not just extra jank."
  });

