  reg({
    id: 'rn-perf-useeffect-cleanup-bug', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-performance',
    difficulty: 'senior', type: 'spot-the-bug',
    prompt: 'After navigating in and out of this screen repeatedly, the app slows down and eventually logs "Can\'t perform a React state update on an unmounted component." What\'s the perf bug?',
    code: "function LiveTicker({ symbol }) {\n  const [price, setPrice] = useState(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const socket = subscribeToPriceFeed(symbol, (nextPrice) => {\n      setPrice(nextPrice);\n    });\n\n    const pollId = setInterval(() => {\n      socket.requestSnapshot();\n    }, 5000);\n\n    // BUG: no cleanup function returned at all — the socket subscription and\n    // the setInterval both keep running (and keep this closure, and setPrice,\n    // and the whole component's fiber, alive) forever after LiveTicker unmounts.\n  }, [symbol]);\n\n  return <Text>{price ?? 'Loading…'}</Text>;\n}",
    answer: "function LiveTicker({ symbol }) {\n  const [price, setPrice] = useState(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const socket = subscribeToPriceFeed(symbol, (nextPrice) => {\n      setPrice(nextPrice);\n    });\n\n    const pollId = setInterval(() => {\n      socket.requestSnapshot();\n    }, 5000);\n\n    return () => {\n      clearInterval(pollId);\n      socket.unsubscribe();\n    };\n  }, [symbol]);\n\n  return <Text>{price ?? 'Loading…'}</Text>;\n}",
    explanation: "The effect registers two live, ongoing resources — a socket subscription and a setInterval — but returns no cleanup function, so neither is ever torn down. On unmount, React stops rendering LiveTicker, but nothing tells the socket to unsubscribe or the interval to stop firing: the interval keeps calling socket.requestSnapshot() and the socket keeps invoking its callback, which calls setPrice on a component that no longer exists, producing the 'state update on an unmounted component' warning (and, on some RN/React versions, a hard error). Worse, each of those callbacks is a closure that keeps the entire effect's scope — including the component instance's fiber and setPrice — reachable by the garbage collector, so navigating to this screen and back N times leaves N leaked subscriptions and N leaked intervals all still firing and all still pinning memory, which is exactly the cumulative slowdown-then-crash pattern described. The fix is a cleanup function that synchronously reverses everything the effect set up — clearInterval for the timer, an explicit unsubscribe/close for the socket — so unmounting the component actually releases every resource and reference the effect created, not just the rendered UI."
  });

